comments.body: It can be H. mabouia, H. garnotii, Lepidodactylus lugubris, Gehyra mutilata or even some natives like Thecadactylus rapicauda and Phyllodactylus spp. Too many possibilities!!!
By probability, it is most likely that it is a specimen of H. frenatus, hence the suggestion of this identification.
How can you tell it is H. frenatus?
